    "curated_by": "Ishmail De Niro",
    "location": "Prayer Room, Birmingham",
    "artists": "Shah Jahan, Baesianz, Sue Tompkins, Poppy Nash, Umar Ahmed",
    "show_artists": "NO",
    "meta_display_override": "",
    "text": "Shah Jahan, Baesianz, Sue Tompkins, Poppy Nash, Umar Ahmed\nI pray for a place for people to visit. Brick and mortar, something local, something tangible and heavy and big. All will be welcome here.\nImagine each and every character you encounter throughout your early adulthood and remember one, what, if anything at all, would you ask that person now, given that chance again?\nFifteen years ago, you meet somebody, stood at a bus stop in sunglasses, headphones and a Maison Margiela x H&M beaver coat, the man that stands before you serves as an introduction, the introduction, to the ominous ‘art world.’\nLeaves are falling from the trees as your Dad drives you to ‘the artist’s studio’. The palette is orange in autumn and it is cold. White walls, wooden floors. A litany of paintings clad the space. Mounted to the walls, resting on the floor, on tables, chairs. Some bubble-wrapped and ready to go, others pristine and freshly painted. They are all of Michael Jackson. Specifically, him as Michael Jackson, in turn as a pizza delivery boy.\nYou feel, undoubtedly, that this artist has ‘made it’. He exhibits internationally, he maintains that air of cool mystique that you, 16-year-old, pine for. Then, he dies.\nIn conceiving If stars ever fell? I wanted to reflect upon artists I have known in a past life, or artists, now, who I desperately want to know. Why does art appeal to us? What problems does it solve? What lessons does it teach? How does it make us feel? What is the role of art-making in a person’s life, before they disappear for good?\nIf stars ever fell accumulates these ideas, appealing to artists who are ‘working it out’. Artists who have ‘made it’, and artists - namely, Shah, stood at the bus stop in his Margiela winter coat - who didn’t. Shah was the first artist I ever knew who was willing to help. At the time, I didn’t know what to ask him. Even if I had believed in God, I wouldn’t have known what to pray for.",
    "Artwork title": "If stars ever fell?",
    "Artwork materials": "Mixed Media",
    "Dimensions": "Dimensions variable",
